# Documentation Style

Write like a colleague explaining to another developer. Be direct and technical.

## Avoid

- Emojis in documentation (no âœ… ğŸš€ ğŸ‰ âš ï¸ etc.)
- Strong-emphasis lists: `- **Label** - Description` or `**Label:** Description`
- Trailing colons on headings: `## Heading:` or `### Section Name:`
- Trailing colons on list items: `- Item Name:` followed by description
- Delivery language: "What Was Delivered", "Mission Accomplished"
- Marketing phrases: "Perfect for", "Built with", "Ideal for"
- Em dashes (â€”) or en dashes (â€“)
- Status tables with checkmarks
- Excessive enthusiasm and exclamation marks
- Meta-documentation about documentation
- ASCII art diagrams (use mermaid instead)
- Project structure trees in README

## Do

- Use plain prose or simple bullet lists
- State facts directly
- Use code examples instead of explanations
- One heading style per document
- Use simple mermaid diagrams when visuals help
- Keep README focused on getting started
